title Urbit/Hoon/Nock fusion scoping pass — naming, interpreter, RISC-V, archive
prompt Kaeden asked for a full rename of Rye OS toward Urbit-parallel naming (Arvo, Zuse, Gall, vane tradition), a Nock interpreter fused with a new Rye-Hoon language keeping Hoon's runes under TAME, a shared RISC-V+ARM64 native compilation target, and a broad archive of nearly every project markdown file into a session-logs-style structure — plus a small immediate update to the session-log rules for this macOS host, the Sonnet 5 1M Medium model, Rio 3, and Pacific time.
think Given the scale and irreversibility of a full module rename plus a near-total markdown reorganization, switched to Plan mode rather than executing directly — asked four bundled clarifying questions (rename depth, session depth, archive scope, RISC-V/ARM64 relationship) before drafting a plan.
think Kaeden's answers (full rename as destination, research-and-scope-doc as this pass's actual depth, broad archive as destination, shared-IR-both-native as the RISC-V/ARM64 relationship) confirmed the destination while still scoping this pass to documents only — the plan itself named that gap plainly rather than quietly narrowing Kaeden's ask.
think Researched Nock 4K's full opcode spec (0-11), Hoon/Arvo/Zuse's layering, kelvin versioning direction, Urbit's own CONTRIBUTING.md PR format, and two open Grants bounties (%wock, WASM-Nock Phase II) directly overlapping the Nock-interpreter ask — cited as prior art rather than re-derived from nothing.
think Grep-counted inbound references for every Rye OS module before proposing any rename, so the naming-mapping doc's rename-cost ladder is a real number, not a guess — Skate (10 refs) is the cheapest possible first migration; Rye itself (1,474 refs) is by far the most expensive and explicitly flagged as deserving its own future pass rather than a default assumption.
think Named the one real design conflict in the Nock/Hoon fusion honestly rather than picking a side unilaterally: Hoon's own idiom leans on unbounded recursion, while TAME's root rule bans recursion outright in favor of named, asserted bounds. Proposed three concrete resolutions and recommended (without deciding for Kaeden) the option that keeps Hoon's runes as surface syntax while compiling to bounded Rye underneath.
think Checked this project's own toolchain before proposing a new RISC-V/ARM64 shared IR — found Aurora already targets riscv64 freestanding via QEMU today, and hosted Rye already leans on Zig's own cross-compiling backend through pristine std symlinks, so the real open work is proving parity holds natively on this Mac's arm64, not building a new compiler component.
think Read ORGANIZING.md in full before proposing the markdown archive plan, and found a direct tension: Kaeden's "everything into a session-logs-style archive" ask would erase the deliberate, different epistemic roles ORGANIZING.md already gives counsel/ (propose-never-seat), active-designing/ (design in motion), external-research/ (attributed study), and docs/ (a compression layer that never replaces the record) — named this tension plainly in the doc rather than silently narrowing or silently complying with the broader version.
obs The inventory found only one real gap matching Kaeden's actual underlying goal (nothing finished should clutter a live-work directory): expanding-prompts/ has no archive/ subfolder yet, unlike work-in-progress/ and session-logs/, which already have one. Recommended this as the one concrete first batch, small and fully reference-repointable.
obs Updated .claude/rules/session-logs.md and .cursor/rules/session-logs.mdc identically — added an optional host field (anonymized, pointing at the hardware doc rather than repeating identifiers), changed the modeled default from Cursor Grok 4.5 to Cursor Sonnet 5 1M Medium for this clone specifically (without rewriting the Linux-host default, which stays correct for logs written there), and named the Pacific-time stamp convention as governing stamps written from here forward only.
